<h2>Event in July 2019</h2>
<strong>Heatwave over Western Europe</strong>
<br><br>
From 24 to 26 July exceptionally high temperatures occurred over the western part of Europe. All-time records for daily maximum temperatures, which had just been broken during the previous heat wave in June, were again surpassed.
<br><br>
Like the previous heat wave in June, the high temperatures resulted from an extensive omega block developed over Europe (see <a href="june2019.php">State-of-the-European-climate June 2019</a> for an explanation of the omega block). With a low pressure system west of Ireland and high pressure in the eastern part of Europe, hot air from the Sahara was transported over Western Europe all the way to Scandinavia with a southerly wind (Figure 1).
<br><br>
In the Netherlands and Belgium for the first time since the beginning of the measurements the daily maximum temperature exceeded 40&#176;C, with a new record of 40.7&#176;C in Gilze-Rijen and 41.8&#176;C in Begijnendijk on the 25th of July respectively. Luxembourg set a new record with 40.8&#176;C in Steinsel, United Kingdom with 38.7&#176;C in Cambridge Botanic Gardens. In western Germany many stations measured three consecutive days with 40&#176;C. A new all-time record for Germany was set in Lingen, not far from the Dutch border, with 42.6&#176;C. Also France recorded many station records in the northern part of the country with for example 42.6&#176;C in Paris-Montsouris, after having record breaking temperatures in the South f France in the previous month of June (with 46.0&#176;C at V&eacute;rargues, Gard, on June 28). The heat wave extended all the way to Scandinavia with locally maximum temperatures in southern Finland over 33&#176;C and in Norway over 34&#176;C.
<br><br>
Figure 2 shows that the maximum temperatures this summer in Western Europe are locally six to eight degrees higher than the average warmest day in a year in the period 1981-2010 (a) and the area where temperature records are broken (in the E-OBS record since 1950) covers a large part of western Europe (b).
