<h2>Specific climate indicators for July 2019</h2>
In the month of July temperatures were on average much higher than normal in parts of southern France and northeastern Spain and also in western en northern parts of Scandinavia. The number of warm days (days with a maximumtemperature > 90th percentile) was very high, especially in the (north)eastern part of Europe. The warm spell duration index (WSDI), defined as the number of consecutive days on which the daily maximum temperature exceeds the 90th percentile, with a minimum of six, is reaching eight to ten at some locations in far northern Europe. In Finland the WDSI is larger than the number of warm days, indicating that during the warm spells the daily minimum temperature was relatively low. Also southeastern France counted six or more consecutive warm days. The low values of the WDSI in the western part of Europe show that the heatwave in this area was short-lived.
<br><br>
<br><br>
