<h2>The weather in July 2019</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
Over large parts of Europe the average temperature in July 2019 was higher than the 1981-2010 average for July, particularly in the west (see Figure 3, middle panel). Compared to June, which was the warmest June ever recorded in several European countries, the July anomalies were in general lower in magnitude. Largest anomalies occurred over France with +3&#176;C above normal. Much above and exceptionally above normal temperatures, corresponding to the 75-90 and > 90 percentile ranges were therefore also only recorded over central and western Europe and over the western part of Scandinavia (see Figure 4, middle panel). During a short but severe heatwave occurring over the western part of Europe on 24 and 25 July (see event description above) daily maximum temperatures exceeded 40&#176;C in many places and many station and country-wide records were broken (see Figure 5, right panel). There were also regions with lower-than-normal temperatures in July, namely the southwestern edge of the Iberian Peninsula and northeastern Europe (Finland, Baltic countries, Belarus, western Russia).
